= Seeking to Understand these Passages (and many others) Leads to the Trinity: #link(<Index>)[↺] <Summary>

- There is exactly one God.

- There are exactly three persons who are properly called God.

According to this, we have a simple description: *God is an immaterial, tri-personal being*.

Some creedal formulations are much more detailed, but this is perhaps the simplest formulation of what could be called the "Biblical Doctrine of the Trinity" (Dr. William Lane Craig)


#pagebreak()

= Errors to Avoid (Historic Heresies) #link(<Index>)[↺] <Heresies>

/ Modalism: God as one person manifesting in three roles (e.g., Father, then Son, then Spirit) – Contradicted by simultaneous presence (Jesus' baptism: Matthew 3:16-17).



/ Tritheism: Belief in three separate gods – Rejected; there is only one God (Deuteronomy 6:4).



/ Subordinationism: Inferiority in essence among the Persons – Rejected; all are equally divine in attributes, though distinct in roles.











